1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,346
Two men in police uniforms walked into

2
00:00:02,413 --> 00:00:04,573
a Boston museum and walked out with

3
00:00:04,640 --> 00:00:07,047
half a billion dollars of masterpieces.

4
00:00:07,114 --> 00:00:08,287
Eighty-one minutes.

5
00:00:08,354 --> 00:00:09,354
Thirteen works.

6
00:00:09,421 --> 00:00:11,519
And more than thirty years later —

7
00:00:11,586 --> 00:00:13,314
not one has ever been found.

8
00:00:15,528 --> 00:00:17,874
Walk into the Isabella Stewart Gardner

9
00:00:17,941 --> 00:00:19,360
Museum in Boston today,

10
00:00:19,427 --> 00:00:21,834
and you will find something that should

11
00:00:21,901 --> 00:00:22,901
not be there.

12
00:00:22,968 --> 00:00:24,006
Or rather —

13
00:00:24,073 --> 00:00:25,369
something that isn't.

14
00:00:27,248 --> 00:00:29,717
On the walls, between the paintings that

15
00:00:29,784 --> 00:00:31,389
remain, hang empty frames.

16
00:00:32,080 --> 00:00:34,740
Gilded, ornate, and holding nothing at

17
00:00:34,807 --> 00:00:35,807
all.

18
00:00:35,940 --> 00:00:37,360
They are not a mistake,

19
00:00:37,427 --> 00:00:38,723
and they are not art.

20
00:00:39,080 --> 00:00:41,420
They are the exact spaces where some

21
00:00:41,487 --> 00:00:43,894
of the most valuable paintings on earth

22
00:00:43,961 --> 00:00:44,961
used to be —

23
00:00:45,028 --> 00:00:47,620
left hanging, deliberately, as a wound the

24
00:00:47,687 --> 00:00:49,353
museum refuses to cover up.

25
00:00:50,920 --> 00:00:53,019
Because on a single night in 1990,

26
00:00:53,320 --> 00:00:54,925
those frames were emptied.

27
00:00:55,120 --> 00:00:57,342
Two men talked their way through the

28
00:00:57,409 --> 00:00:58,952
door, tied up the guards,

29
00:00:59,019 --> 00:01:01,117
and spent the next hour and twenty

30
00:01:01,184 --> 00:01:03,406
minutes taking thirteen works of art

31
00:01:03,473 --> 00:01:05,078
worth, by common estimate,

32
00:01:05,145 --> 00:01:06,997
around half a billion dollars.

33
00:01:07,733 --> 00:01:09,523
The FBI would come to call it

34
00:01:09,590 --> 00:01:12,121
the largest property crime in the history

35
00:01:12,188 --> 00:01:13,484
of the United States.

36
00:01:13,551 --> 00:01:15,711
The museum calls it the largest art

37
00:01:15,778 --> 00:01:16,827
heist in history.

38
00:01:16,894 --> 00:01:18,437
And whatever you call it,

39
00:01:18,504 --> 00:01:20,541
it shares one more title that has

40
00:01:20,608 --> 00:01:22,460
never changed: it is unsolved.

41
00:01:23,340 --> 00:01:25,377
No one has ever been charged with

42
00:01:25,444 --> 00:01:26,444
the theft.

43
00:01:26,511 --> 00:01:28,486
Not a single one of the thirteen

44
00:01:28,553 --> 00:01:30,405
works has ever been recovered.

45
00:01:30,472 --> 00:01:32,694
The thieves have never been publicly

46
00:01:32,761 --> 00:01:33,761
named.

47
00:01:33,828 --> 00:01:35,803
And the empty frames still hang,

48
00:01:35,870 --> 00:01:36,870
waiting.

49
00:01:36,937 --> 00:01:38,912
We are drawn to crimes that end.

50
00:01:38,979 --> 00:01:40,584
The confession, the trial,

51
00:01:40,651 --> 00:01:42,811
the verdict, the cell door closing.

52
00:01:43,700 --> 00:01:45,675
This is not one of those crimes.

53
00:01:45,960 --> 00:01:47,750
This is the one that got away

54
00:01:47,817 --> 00:01:50,101
so completely that it has slipped out

55
00:01:50,168 --> 00:01:52,081
of the world of police work and

56
00:01:52,148 --> 00:01:54,000
into something like folklore —

57
00:01:54,067 --> 00:01:56,042
except the loss is utterly real,

58
00:01:56,109 --> 00:01:57,899
and you can stand in front of

59
00:01:57,966 --> 00:01:58,966
it.

60
00:01:59,033 --> 00:02:01,255
That is what makes the Gardner heist

61
00:02:01,322 --> 00:02:02,322
different.

62
00:02:02,389 --> 00:02:04,117
There is no ending to spoil.

63
00:02:04,184 --> 00:02:06,159
Only an absence, framed in gold,

64
00:02:06,226 --> 00:02:08,571
that has been waiting longer than many

65
00:02:08,638 --> 00:02:10,922
of the people watching this have been

66
00:02:10,989 --> 00:02:11,989
alive.

67
00:02:12,340 --> 00:02:14,007
This is the story of how it

68
00:02:14,074 --> 00:02:15,205
happened —

69
00:02:15,272 --> 00:02:16,321
minute by minute.

70
00:02:16,388 --> 00:02:18,672
What exactly vanished, and why it can

71
00:02:18,739 --> 00:02:20,035
never simply be sold.

72
00:02:20,180 --> 00:02:22,464
Everything the FBI will and won't say

73
00:02:22,531 --> 00:02:23,580
about who did it.

74
00:02:23,647 --> 00:02:25,992
And why, after more than three decades

75
00:02:26,059 --> 00:02:28,034
and a ten-million-dollar reward,

76
00:02:28,101 --> 00:02:30,076
the most famous art theft in the

77
00:02:30,143 --> 00:02:32,303
world is still a mystery with empty

78
00:02:32,370 --> 00:02:33,666
frames for an answer.

79
00:02:33,733 --> 00:02:35,770
It begins, as the best heists do,

80
00:02:35,837 --> 00:02:37,689
with a quiet night and a small

81
00:02:37,756 --> 00:02:38,756
lie.

82
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:42,735
It is the early morning of March

83
00:02:42,802 --> 00:02:43,802
18th, 1990.

84
00:02:44,080 --> 00:02:46,302
Boston is still coming down from St.

85
00:02:46,369 --> 00:02:47,369
Patrick's Day.

86
00:02:47,436 --> 00:02:49,781
The streets near the museum are empty.

87
00:02:49,848 --> 00:02:52,132
Inside, two young security guards are

88
00:02:52,199 --> 00:02:54,421
doing the most ordinary thing in the

89
00:02:54,488 --> 00:02:55,488
world —

90
00:02:55,555 --> 00:02:57,900
watching a building where nothing ever

91
00:02:57,967 --> 00:02:58,967
happens.

92
00:02:59,034 --> 00:03:00,886
At around half past one in the

93
00:03:00,953 --> 00:03:03,051
morning, a buzzer sounds at a side

94
00:03:03,118 --> 00:03:04,118
entrance.

95
00:03:04,185 --> 00:03:06,716
Outside stand two men in police uniforms.

96
00:03:06,783 --> 00:03:08,820
They say they are responding to a

97
00:03:08,887 --> 00:03:11,232
disturbance, a call about the grounds.

98
00:03:11,299 --> 00:03:12,472
They look the part.

99
00:03:12,539 --> 00:03:13,773
They sound the part.

100
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:15,692
And here is the first hinge of

101
00:03:15,759 --> 00:03:16,808
the whole story —

102
00:03:16,875 --> 00:03:18,356
a single human decision.

103
00:03:18,423 --> 00:03:19,534
One of the guards,

104
00:03:19,601 --> 00:03:21,514
against the museum's own rules,

105
00:03:21,581 --> 00:03:22,581
buzzes them in.

106
00:03:22,880 --> 00:03:24,361
It is the kind of small,

107
00:03:24,428 --> 00:03:26,897
understandable mistake anyone might make

108
00:03:26,964 --> 00:03:29,001
at one-thirty in the morning when

109
00:03:29,068 --> 00:03:31,166
authority is standing at the door.

110
00:03:31,233 --> 00:03:32,899
He had no way of knowing it

111
00:03:32,966 --> 00:03:35,497
would become the most expensive door ever

112
00:03:35,564 --> 00:03:36,564
opened.

113
00:03:36,631 --> 00:03:38,544
It is worth pausing on why that

114
00:03:38,611 --> 00:03:40,956
worked, because it is the quiet engine

115
00:03:41,023 --> 00:03:42,196
of the whole crime.

116
00:03:42,263 --> 00:03:43,868
A uniform is a kind of key

117
00:03:43,935 --> 00:03:45,972
that opens doors no lockpick can.

118
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:47,685
We are trained, all of us,

119
00:03:47,752 --> 00:03:50,221
to relax a little when authority arrives

120
00:03:50,640 --> 00:03:51,640
—

121
00:03:51,707 --> 00:03:53,682
to assume that the person in the

122
00:03:53,749 --> 00:03:55,230
uniform is the solution,

123
00:03:55,297 --> 00:03:56,297
not the threat.

124
00:03:56,364 --> 00:03:58,154
The thieves did not break in.

125
00:03:58,221 --> 00:03:59,517
They were invited in,

126
00:03:59,584 --> 00:04:01,806
by a frightened young man doing what

127
00:04:01,873 --> 00:04:03,601
most of us would do when the

128
00:04:03,668 --> 00:04:05,458
police say there's a problem.

129
00:04:05,525 --> 00:04:08,056
The first and biggest security system the

130
00:04:08,123 --> 00:04:09,789
museum had was human trust.

131
00:04:09,856 --> 00:04:12,016
And it was defeated with a costume.

132
00:04:12,860 --> 00:04:14,959
Once inside, the men move quickly.

133
00:04:15,100 --> 00:04:16,952
They tell the guard there is a

134
00:04:17,019 --> 00:04:18,760
warrant for his arrest —

135
00:04:18,827 --> 00:04:20,617
and ask him to step away from

136
00:04:20,684 --> 00:04:23,029
the only alarm button in the building.

137
00:04:23,096 --> 00:04:24,096
He does.

138
00:04:24,163 --> 00:04:26,385
They call the second guard down too.

139
00:04:26,452 --> 00:04:28,550
And in moments, the costume drops,

140
00:04:28,617 --> 00:04:30,777
and the truth is obvious: these are

141
00:04:30,844 --> 00:04:31,844
not police.

142
00:04:32,620 --> 00:04:34,225
The guards are handcuffed,

143
00:04:34,292 --> 00:04:36,020
walked down to the basement,

144
00:04:36,087 --> 00:04:37,087
and bound —

145
00:04:37,154 --> 00:04:39,623
their wrists cuffed, their heads wrapped

146
00:04:39,690 --> 00:04:40,690
in duct tape.

147
00:04:40,757 --> 00:04:42,300
And there they will stay,

148
00:04:42,367 --> 00:04:43,663
helpless in the dark,

149
00:04:43,730 --> 00:04:46,075
while above them the most valuable art

150
00:04:46,142 --> 00:04:48,487
theft in history unfolds in real time.

151
00:04:48,554 --> 00:04:50,899
Remember that: the guards were victims

152
00:04:50,966 --> 00:04:51,966
too.

153
00:04:52,033 --> 00:04:54,008
They were tied up in a basement,

154
00:04:54,075 --> 00:04:55,494
not let in on a secret.

155
00:04:55,561 --> 00:04:57,474
Now the thieves have the run of

156
00:04:57,541 --> 00:04:58,541
the museum.

157
00:04:58,608 --> 00:05:00,768
And the building is watching them —

158
00:05:00,835 --> 00:05:01,835
silently.

159
00:05:01,902 --> 00:05:04,186
Motion detectors quietly record their

160
00:05:04,253 --> 00:05:06,598
movements as they move from gallery to

161
00:05:06,665 --> 00:05:07,665
gallery.

162
00:05:07,732 --> 00:05:10,077
There is, somewhere, a record of their

163
00:05:10,144 --> 00:05:11,440
footsteps that night.

164
00:05:11,507 --> 00:05:12,618
What there is not,

165
00:05:12,685 --> 00:05:13,734
is a single face.

166
00:05:13,801 --> 00:05:15,159
Picture the next hour.

167
00:05:15,226 --> 00:05:16,954
A great museum at two in the

168
00:05:17,021 --> 00:05:18,564
morning, dark and hushed,

169
00:05:18,631 --> 00:05:20,915
hung with centuries of masterpieces —

170
00:05:20,982 --> 00:05:23,204
and two men moving through it alone,

171
00:05:23,271 --> 00:05:24,567
in no apparent hurry,

172
00:05:24,634 --> 00:05:26,547
with all the time in the world.

173
00:05:27,040 --> 00:05:29,015
No alarm rang out to the police.

174
00:05:29,460 --> 00:05:32,053
The only witnesses were the silent sensors

175
00:05:32,120 --> 00:05:34,218
in the ceilings and the two guards

176
00:05:34,285 --> 00:05:36,013
bound in the basement below,

177
00:05:36,080 --> 00:05:38,672
listening to footsteps overhead and unable

178
00:05:38,739 --> 00:05:40,591
to do a single thing about it.

179
00:05:40,658 --> 00:05:42,571
It is one of the eeriest scenes

180
00:05:42,638 --> 00:05:44,922
in the history of crime: an unhurried

181
00:05:44,989 --> 00:05:46,779
robbery of the irreplaceable,

182
00:05:46,846 --> 00:05:48,265
with no one to stop it.

183
00:05:49,293 --> 00:05:51,268
They go first to the Dutch Room,

184
00:05:51,335 --> 00:05:52,569
on the second floor,

185
00:05:52,636 --> 00:05:53,994
where the giants hang.

186
00:05:54,061 --> 00:05:56,345
And here they do something that still

187
00:05:56,412 --> 00:05:58,078
makes art historians wince.

188
00:05:58,145 --> 00:06:00,676
Rather than carefully lift the paintings,

189
00:06:00,743 --> 00:06:03,212
they cut two enormous Rembrandt canvases

190
00:06:03,279 --> 00:06:04,513
out of their frames.

191
00:06:04,580 --> 00:06:06,740
You can almost feel the violence of

192
00:06:06,807 --> 00:06:07,807
it —

193
00:06:07,874 --> 00:06:08,874
a blade against

194
00:06:08,941 --> 00:06:11,348
three-hundred-and-fifty-year-old paint.

195
00:06:11,415 --> 00:06:13,081
They work for over an hour.

196
00:06:13,148 --> 00:06:14,629
Methodical in some ways,

197
00:06:14,696 --> 00:06:15,869
baffling in others.

198
00:06:15,936 --> 00:06:18,158
They take some masterpieces and walk

199
00:06:18,225 --> 00:06:20,756
straight past others that were worth even

200
00:06:20,823 --> 00:06:21,823
more.

201
00:06:21,890 --> 00:06:24,112
They ignore the single most valuable

202
00:06:24,179 --> 00:06:26,648
painting in the building by one measure,

203
00:06:26,715 --> 00:06:28,999
and grab an ordinary bronze eagle off

204
00:06:29,066 --> 00:06:30,066
a flagpole.

205
00:06:30,133 --> 00:06:32,170
Whatever this was, it was not the

206
00:06:32,237 --> 00:06:34,335
work of refined art thieves with a

207
00:06:34,402 --> 00:06:35,402
shopping list.

208
00:06:35,469 --> 00:06:37,197
At a quarter to three in the

209
00:06:37,264 --> 00:06:38,560
morning, they leave —

210
00:06:38,627 --> 00:06:40,725
making two separate trips out to a

211
00:06:40,792 --> 00:06:41,792
car, arms full.

212
00:06:41,859 --> 00:06:42,859
The doors close.

213
00:06:42,926 --> 00:06:45,086
The museum sits silent over its two

214
00:06:45,153 --> 00:06:46,153
bound guards.

215
00:06:46,220 --> 00:06:48,318
And by the time anyone arrives the

216
00:06:48,385 --> 00:06:49,990
next morning to find them,

217
00:06:50,057 --> 00:06:51,600
the thieves, and the art,

218
00:06:51,667 --> 00:06:52,667
are simply gone.

219
00:06:52,734 --> 00:06:54,894
Morning comes to the museum the way

220
00:06:54,961 --> 00:06:55,961
it always does.

221
00:06:56,028 --> 00:06:58,373
A staff member arrives for an ordinary

222
00:06:58,440 --> 00:07:00,477
shift and finds the unthinkable —

223
00:07:00,544 --> 00:07:03,136
two colleagues handcuffed in the basement,

224
00:07:03,203 --> 00:07:05,363
and upstairs, raw gaps on the walls

225
00:07:05,430 --> 00:07:07,837
where the world's masterpieces had hung

226
00:07:07,904 --> 00:07:08,953
the night before.

227
00:07:09,020 --> 00:07:10,378
The police are called.

228
00:07:10,445 --> 00:07:12,111
The frames are found empty,

229
00:07:12,178 --> 00:07:14,462
some with their canvases sliced clean

230
00:07:14,529 --> 00:07:15,529
away.

231
00:07:15,596 --> 00:07:17,324
In a single overnight shift,

232
00:07:17,391 --> 00:07:19,798
the Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum had

233
00:07:19,865 --> 00:07:22,025
become the scene of the largest art

234
00:07:22,092 --> 00:07:23,820
theft anyone had ever seen —

235
00:07:23,887 --> 00:07:25,862
and the clock that would run for

236
00:07:25,929 --> 00:07:27,410
decades, with no answer,

237
00:07:27,477 --> 00:07:28,711
had already started.

238
00:07:28,778 --> 00:07:31,000
Eighty-one minutes, start to finish.

239
00:07:31,067 --> 00:07:32,919
It is the last time anyone can

240
00:07:32,986 --> 00:07:35,578
say for certain where those thirteen works

241
00:07:35,645 --> 00:07:36,645
were.

242
00:07:36,712 --> 00:07:38,996
So what, exactly, walked out the door

243
00:07:39,063 --> 00:07:40,063
that night?

244
00:07:41,318 --> 00:07:43,033
Thirteen works in all —

245
00:07:43,100 --> 00:07:45,013
and not the tidy haul you might

246
00:07:45,080 --> 00:07:46,080
imagine.

247
00:07:46,147 --> 00:07:47,147
It is a strange,

248
00:07:47,214 --> 00:07:49,683
uneven list, and that strangeness is one

249
00:07:49,750 --> 00:07:51,787
of the great clues that has never

250
00:07:51,854 --> 00:07:52,965
quite been solved.

251
00:07:54,013 --> 00:07:55,741
The crown of it was a single

252
00:07:55,808 --> 00:07:57,598
painting by Johannes Vermeer,

253
00:07:57,665 --> 00:07:59,887
called "The Concert." Vermeer barely

254
00:07:59,954 --> 00:08:00,954
painted.

255
00:08:01,021 --> 00:08:03,181
Only about three dozen of his works

256
00:08:03,248 --> 00:08:05,532
are known to exist anywhere on earth.

257
00:08:05,599 --> 00:08:07,451
"The Concert" is one of them —

258
00:08:07,518 --> 00:08:09,431
and both the museum and the FBI

259
00:08:09,498 --> 00:08:11,473
have called it the most valuable

260
00:08:11,540 --> 00:08:13,638
unrecovered painting in the world.

261
00:08:13,705 --> 00:08:15,989
A quiet scene of people making music,

262
00:08:16,056 --> 00:08:17,846
now itself completely silent,

263
00:08:17,913 --> 00:08:20,135
its location unknown for over thirty

264
00:08:20,202 --> 00:08:21,202
years.

265
00:08:21,269 --> 00:08:23,861
To understand why losing that one painting

266
00:08:23,928 --> 00:08:26,335
matters so much, you have to understand

267
00:08:26,402 --> 00:08:28,624
how little Vermeer there is to lose.

268
00:08:28,691 --> 00:08:30,604
He worked slowly, died in debt,

269
00:08:30,671 --> 00:08:32,646
and left behind only a few dozen

270
00:08:32,713 --> 00:08:34,503
paintings in his entire life.

271
00:08:34,570 --> 00:08:36,915
Each one that survives is treated like

272
00:08:36,982 --> 00:08:39,574
a national treasure by whatever country is

273
00:08:39,641 --> 00:08:41,122
lucky enough to hold it.

274
00:08:41,189 --> 00:08:42,855
To have one simply vanish —

275
00:08:42,922 --> 00:08:44,712
cut out of the world for over

276
00:08:44,779 --> 00:08:46,754
thirty years, its fate unknown —

277
00:08:46,821 --> 00:08:49,105
is not like losing a valuable object.

278
00:08:49,172 --> 00:08:50,345
It is like a small,

279
00:08:50,412 --> 00:08:52,757
permanent hole in the history of human

280
00:08:52,824 --> 00:08:53,824
art.

281
00:08:53,891 --> 00:08:55,434
Then there was Rembrandt.

282
00:08:55,501 --> 00:08:57,661
They took his "A Lady and Gentleman

283
00:08:57,728 --> 00:08:58,821
in Black," and —

284
00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:00,903
the one that hurts most —

285
00:09:01,300 --> 00:09:03,214
"Christ in the Storm on the Sea

286
00:09:03,281 --> 00:09:05,460
of Galilee." It is a large,

287
00:09:05,527 --> 00:09:07,920
dramatic painting of a boat caught in

288
00:09:07,987 --> 00:09:10,080
a furious sea, and it carries a

289
00:09:10,147 --> 00:09:12,480
haunting distinction: it is the only

290
00:09:12,547 --> 00:09:15,016
seascape Rembrandt is known to have ever

291
00:09:15,083 --> 00:09:16,083
painted.

292
00:09:16,150 --> 00:09:17,150
The only one.

293
00:09:17,217 --> 00:09:19,007
And it was cut from its frame

294
00:09:19,074 --> 00:09:21,049
in the dark and carried into the

295
00:09:21,116 --> 00:09:22,116
night.

296
00:09:22,183 --> 00:09:24,096
But here is where the list gets

297
00:09:24,163 --> 00:09:25,163
strange.

298
00:09:25,230 --> 00:09:27,761
Alongside the Vermeer and the Rembrandts,

299
00:09:27,828 --> 00:09:30,050
the thieves took five works by Degas

300
00:09:30,117 --> 00:09:31,117
—

301
00:09:31,184 --> 00:09:33,715
small, delicate sketches and watercolors,

302
00:09:33,782 --> 00:09:36,251
not the artist's most famous or valuable

303
00:09:36,318 --> 00:09:37,318
pieces.

304
00:09:37,385 --> 00:09:38,496
They took a Manet.

305
00:09:38,563 --> 00:09:40,723
And then they took two objects that

306
00:09:40,790 --> 00:09:43,197
belong in an entirely different kind of

307
00:09:43,264 --> 00:09:44,264
crime.

308
00:09:44,331 --> 00:09:46,491
One was an ancient Chinese beaker —

309
00:09:46,558 --> 00:09:48,286
a bronze vessel called a Gu,

310
00:09:48,353 --> 00:09:50,205
some three thousand years old.

311
00:09:50,272 --> 00:09:52,432
The other was a small bronze eagle,

312
00:09:52,499 --> 00:09:54,412
a finial that had once topped a

313
00:09:54,479 --> 00:09:57,071
flagstaff belonging to Napoleon's imperial

314
00:09:57,138 --> 00:09:58,138
guard.

315
00:09:58,205 --> 00:09:59,501
Not paintings at all.

316
00:09:59,568 --> 00:10:01,975
Odd, specific, almost personal choices.

317
00:10:02,647 --> 00:10:05,116
And running underneath the whole list is

318
00:10:05,183 --> 00:10:06,183
a riddle.

319
00:10:06,250 --> 00:10:08,719
The thieves walked right past works that

320
00:10:08,786 --> 00:10:11,255
experts say were more valuable than some

321
00:10:11,322 --> 00:10:12,433
of what they took.

322
00:10:12,500 --> 00:10:14,722
They spent precious minutes prying a

323
00:10:14,789 --> 00:10:16,270
bronze eagle off a pole.

324
00:10:16,337 --> 00:10:18,682
People who study this case have argued

325
00:10:18,749 --> 00:10:20,786
for decades over what that means.

326
00:10:20,853 --> 00:10:23,137
Were they amateurs grabbing what they

327
00:10:23,204 --> 00:10:24,204
recognized?

328
00:10:24,271 --> 00:10:26,555
Were they working from someone else's

329
00:10:26,622 --> 00:10:27,622
list?

330
00:10:27,689 --> 00:10:30,034
Or did the strange haul mean something

331
00:10:30,101 --> 00:10:31,706
we still don't understand?

332
00:10:31,773 --> 00:10:33,871
That oddness is not a small detail

333
00:10:33,938 --> 00:10:34,938
—

334
00:10:35,005 --> 00:10:36,548
it is one of the few real

335
00:10:36,615 --> 00:10:38,467
clues the thieves left behind.

336
00:10:38,534 --> 00:10:40,879
Professional art thieves, the kind who

337
00:10:40,946 --> 00:10:43,168
steal to order, tend to be surgical:

338
00:10:43,235 --> 00:10:44,963
they take the most valuable,

339
00:10:45,030 --> 00:10:47,499
most portable pieces and leave the rest.

340
00:10:47,566 --> 00:10:50,097
These thieves did something closer to the

341
00:10:50,164 --> 00:10:51,164
opposite.

342
00:10:51,231 --> 00:10:53,762
They damaged masterpieces by cutting them

343
00:10:53,829 --> 00:10:54,829
out.

344
00:10:54,896 --> 00:10:57,056
They skipped works of immense value

345
00:10:57,123 --> 00:10:58,123
hanging nearby.

346
00:10:58,190 --> 00:11:00,165
They spent their limited minutes

347
00:11:00,232 --> 00:11:02,577
unscrewing a bronze eagle from a pole.

348
00:11:02,644 --> 00:11:04,619
Decades later, investigators and

349
00:11:04,686 --> 00:11:07,217
historians still cannot fully explain the

350
00:11:07,284 --> 00:11:08,284
logic —

351
00:11:08,351 --> 00:11:10,449
and the haul itself remains one of

352
00:11:10,516 --> 00:11:12,800
the most-studied riddles in the case.

353
00:11:12,867 --> 00:11:15,151
And then there is the number everyone

354
00:11:15,218 --> 00:11:17,193
repeats: half a billion dollars.

355
00:11:17,260 --> 00:11:18,988
Around five hundred million.

356
00:11:19,055 --> 00:11:20,721
It is a staggering figure —

357
00:11:20,788 --> 00:11:22,701
and you have to be careful with

358
00:11:22,768 --> 00:11:23,768
it.

359
00:11:23,835 --> 00:11:25,995
Because that number is an estimate,

360
00:11:26,062 --> 00:11:27,062
not a price.

361
00:11:27,129 --> 00:11:29,104
These works are some of the most

362
00:11:29,171 --> 00:11:31,763
recognizable stolen objects on the planet.

363
00:11:31,830 --> 00:11:34,114
You cannot walk into an auction house

364
00:11:34,181 --> 00:11:35,724
with a cut-out Rembrandt.

365
00:11:35,791 --> 00:11:37,457
The museum itself has said,

366
00:11:37,524 --> 00:11:39,622
bluntly, that it is the only buyer

367
00:11:39,689 --> 00:11:40,689
for these works.

368
00:11:40,756 --> 00:11:43,101
Which means their true value is almost

369
00:11:43,168 --> 00:11:44,168
philosophical —

370
00:11:44,235 --> 00:11:46,766
they are priceless precisely because they

371
00:11:46,833 --> 00:11:47,944
can never be sold.

372
00:11:48,011 --> 00:11:49,924
In the movies there is always a

373
00:11:49,991 --> 00:11:51,164
shadowy collector —

374
00:11:51,231 --> 00:11:53,823
some billionaire who buys a stolen Vermeer

375
00:11:53,890 --> 00:11:55,556
to gloat over it alone in a

376
00:11:55,623 --> 00:11:56,623
hidden vault.

377
00:11:56,690 --> 00:11:59,221
In reality, investigators say that figure

378
00:11:59,288 --> 00:12:00,337
is mostly a myth.

379
00:12:00,404 --> 00:12:02,502
There is no orderly market for the

380
00:12:02,569 --> 00:12:04,853
most recognizable stolen paintings on

381
00:12:04,920 --> 00:12:05,920
earth.

382
00:12:05,987 --> 00:12:07,715
They are too famous to hang,

383
00:12:07,782 --> 00:12:08,782
too hot to sell,

384
00:12:08,849 --> 00:12:10,947
and worth a fortune only on paper.

385
00:12:11,014 --> 00:12:13,545
Which leaves whoever ended up holding the

386
00:12:13,612 --> 00:12:16,204
Gardner art with a peculiar curse: sitting

387
00:12:16,271 --> 00:12:18,369
on half a billion dollars they can

388
00:12:18,436 --> 00:12:19,732
never actually spend.

389
00:12:19,799 --> 00:12:20,910
That single fact —

390
00:12:20,977 --> 00:12:21,977
unsellable —

391
00:12:22,044 --> 00:12:24,204
is the key to everything that comes

392
00:12:24,271 --> 00:12:25,271
next.

393
00:12:25,338 --> 00:12:27,622
Because it changes what kind of crime

394
00:12:27,689 --> 00:12:28,689
this even was.

395
00:12:28,756 --> 00:12:31,163
Most thefts are about turning an object

396
00:12:31,230 --> 00:12:32,230
into money.

397
00:12:32,297 --> 00:12:34,766
But thirteen of the most famous artworks

398
00:12:34,833 --> 00:12:36,931
in the world cannot be turned into

399
00:12:36,998 --> 00:12:37,998
money.

400
00:12:38,065 --> 00:12:40,534
So either the thieves did not understand

401
00:12:40,601 --> 00:12:41,601
that —

402
00:12:41,668 --> 00:12:43,581
or the art was never really the

403
00:12:43,648 --> 00:12:44,648
point.

404
00:12:44,715 --> 00:12:46,937
And every theory about who did this,

405
00:12:47,004 --> 00:12:49,288
and why, has to answer that question.

406
00:12:49,355 --> 00:12:51,083
A crime this big does not go

407
00:12:51,150 --> 00:12:52,150
quietly.

408
00:12:52,217 --> 00:12:54,377
The hunt for the Gardner art became

409
00:12:54,444 --> 00:12:56,172
one of the largest art-crime

410
00:12:56,239 --> 00:12:58,091
investigations in FBI history,

411
00:12:58,158 --> 00:13:00,195
and it has never formally closed.

412
00:13:00,262 --> 00:13:01,435
In the early years,

413
00:13:01,502 --> 00:13:03,477
the trail was hot and useless at

414
00:13:03,544 --> 00:13:04,544
the same time.

415
00:13:04,611 --> 00:13:05,722
Thousands of tips.

416
00:13:05,789 --> 00:13:06,789
Psychics.

417
00:13:06,856 --> 00:13:09,016
Con men claiming they could get the

418
00:13:09,083 --> 00:13:10,083
paintings back —

419
00:13:10,150 --> 00:13:11,150
for a price.

420
00:13:11,217 --> 00:13:12,822
The case drew the curious,

421
00:13:12,889 --> 00:13:14,864
the criminal, and the desperate,

422
00:13:14,931 --> 00:13:17,091
and almost none of it led anywhere.

423
00:13:17,805 --> 00:13:19,472
For a case with so few hard

424
00:13:19,539 --> 00:13:21,761
facts, it generated an extraordinary

425
00:13:21,828 --> 00:13:23,062
amount of attention.

426
00:13:23,129 --> 00:13:24,734
It became, over the years,

427
00:13:24,801 --> 00:13:27,085
the most famous unsolved art theft in

428
00:13:27,152 --> 00:13:28,152
the world —

429
00:13:28,219 --> 00:13:29,515
the subject of books,

430
00:13:29,582 --> 00:13:31,989
documentaries, podcasts, and an endless

431
00:13:32,056 --> 00:13:34,463
stream of armchair detectives convinced

432
00:13:34,530 --> 00:13:35,764
they had cracked it.

433
00:13:35,831 --> 00:13:38,238
The FBI fielded thousands of leads from

434
00:13:38,305 --> 00:13:40,280
across the country and overseas.

435
00:13:40,347 --> 00:13:42,260
And that is part of the tragedy

436
00:13:42,327 --> 00:13:44,364
of a mystery this large: the more

437
00:13:44,431 --> 00:13:46,653
famous it becomes, the more noise it

438
00:13:46,720 --> 00:13:48,818
generates, and the harder it is to

439
00:13:48,885 --> 00:13:50,922
tell a real whisper from the roar

440
00:13:50,989 --> 00:13:52,902
of people who simply want to be

441
00:13:52,969 --> 00:13:54,080
part of the story.

442
00:13:54,147 --> 00:13:56,554
One painful thread ran back through the

443
00:13:56,621 --> 00:13:57,794
museum's own door —

444
00:13:57,861 --> 00:13:59,774
the guard who buzzed the men in

445
00:13:59,841 --> 00:14:00,841
that night.

446
00:14:00,908 --> 00:14:03,439
Investigators looked at him closely; that

447
00:14:03,506 --> 00:14:05,481
is simply what investigators do.

448
00:14:05,548 --> 00:14:07,646
But it is important to be precise:

449
00:14:07,713 --> 00:14:09,873
he was never charged with anything,

450
00:14:09,940 --> 00:14:11,606
and he was found tied up in

451
00:14:11,673 --> 00:14:13,401
that basement with the rest.

452
00:14:13,468 --> 00:14:15,690
Being scrutinized is not the same as

453
00:14:15,757 --> 00:14:18,349
being guilty, and decades of suspicion are

454
00:14:18,416 --> 00:14:20,391
their own kind of sentence for a

455
00:14:20,458 --> 00:14:22,618
man who was never accused in court.

456
00:14:22,685 --> 00:14:23,796
And that caution —

457
00:14:23,863 --> 00:14:26,208
the difference between a suspect and a

458
00:14:26,275 --> 00:14:27,275
thief —

459
00:14:27,342 --> 00:14:29,194
is the thread you have to hold

460
00:14:29,261 --> 00:14:30,804
through this entire case.

461
00:14:30,871 --> 00:14:32,476
Because over thirty years,

462
00:14:32,543 --> 00:14:34,580
a great many names have surfaced.

463
00:14:34,647 --> 00:14:35,647
Local criminals.

464
00:14:35,714 --> 00:14:36,714
Mob figures.

465
00:14:36,781 --> 00:14:38,941
Men who claimed they knew where the

466
00:14:39,008 --> 00:14:40,798
art was, or knew who took it,

467
00:14:40,865 --> 00:14:42,161
or wanted the reward.

468
00:14:42,228 --> 00:14:44,450
But here is the discipline the facts

469
00:14:44,517 --> 00:14:45,517
demand.

470
00:14:45,584 --> 00:14:47,559
Not one of those people has ever

471
00:14:47,626 --> 00:14:49,354
been charged with the theft.

472
00:14:49,421 --> 00:14:51,643
The FBI has never publicly named the

473
00:14:51,710 --> 00:14:52,710
thieves.

474
00:14:52,777 --> 00:14:55,246
And the men sometimes described in books

475
00:14:55,313 --> 00:14:57,720
and documentaries as the likely robbers

476
00:14:57,787 --> 00:15:00,194
were named by journalists and authors —

477
00:15:00,261 --> 00:15:01,372
not by the Bureau.

478
00:15:01,439 --> 00:15:03,414
Some of the people who have been

479
00:15:03,481 --> 00:15:05,579
linked to this case over the years

480
00:15:05,646 --> 00:15:06,646
are still alive.

481
00:15:06,713 --> 00:15:08,565
And a theory is not a verdict.

482
00:15:08,632 --> 00:15:10,298
So we are going to tell you

483
00:15:10,365 --> 00:15:12,834
what law enforcement has actually said —

484
00:15:12,901 --> 00:15:15,493
and stop exactly where the evidence stops.

485
00:15:15,560 --> 00:15:17,720
What law enforcement has said came,

486
00:15:17,787 --> 00:15:19,145
most clearly, in 2013.

487
00:15:19,212 --> 00:15:21,557
On the twenty-third anniversary of the

488
00:15:21,624 --> 00:15:23,476
heist, the FBI made a striking

489
00:15:23,543 --> 00:15:24,543
announcement.

490
00:15:24,610 --> 00:15:25,906
It said it believed —

491
00:15:25,973 --> 00:15:28,010
with what it called a high degree

492
00:15:28,077 --> 00:15:29,077
of confidence —

493
00:15:29,144 --> 00:15:31,242
that it had finally identified the

494
00:15:31,309 --> 00:15:32,309
thieves.

495
00:15:32,376 --> 00:15:34,042
But it would not name them.

496
00:15:34,109 --> 00:15:36,454
The FBI described them only as members

497
00:15:36,521 --> 00:15:38,928
of a criminal organization based in the

498
00:15:38,995 --> 00:15:41,217
Mid-Atlantic states and New England.

499
00:15:41,284 --> 00:15:43,691
And it said something that reframed the

500
00:15:43,758 --> 00:15:45,918
entire case: the people it believed

501
00:15:45,985 --> 00:15:47,775
responsible were likely dead.

502
00:15:47,842 --> 00:15:49,940
Two years later, the Bureau put it

503
00:15:50,007 --> 00:15:51,180
even more plainly —

504
00:15:51,247 --> 00:15:53,160
the two men who carried out the

505
00:15:53,227 --> 00:15:55,079
heist, it said, were deceased.

506
00:15:55,146 --> 00:15:57,430
It was a strange kind of announcement

507
00:15:57,497 --> 00:15:58,497
—

508
00:15:58,564 --> 00:16:00,230
a triumph and a dead end in

509
00:16:00,297 --> 00:16:01,297
the same breath.

510
00:16:01,364 --> 00:16:02,783
The FBI was, in effect,

511
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:05,120
saying: we have solved the part of

512
00:16:05,187 --> 00:16:07,162
the case that no longer matters,

513
00:16:07,229 --> 00:16:08,957
and lost the part that does.

514
00:16:09,340 --> 00:16:11,377
We believe we know the hands that

515
00:16:11,444 --> 00:16:12,617
took the paintings.

516
00:16:12,684 --> 00:16:14,536
We just can no longer ask them

517
00:16:14,603 --> 00:16:15,603
anything —

518
00:16:15,670 --> 00:16:17,583
and they can no longer give the

519
00:16:17,650 --> 00:16:18,650
art back.

520
00:16:18,997 --> 00:16:20,540
Sit with what that means.

521
00:16:21,020 --> 00:16:22,995
The FBI is telling you it thinks

522
00:16:23,062 --> 00:16:25,284
it knows who walked into that museum

523
00:16:25,351 --> 00:16:26,351
—

524
00:16:26,418 --> 00:16:28,455
and that those men are now beyond

525
00:16:28,522 --> 00:16:29,522
any courtroom.

526
00:16:29,589 --> 00:16:31,873
The question was never really "can we

527
00:16:31,940 --> 00:16:33,606
catch them." For years now,

528
00:16:33,673 --> 00:16:35,586
the question has been narrower,

529
00:16:35,653 --> 00:16:37,628
and sadder: where did the art go

530
00:16:37,695 --> 00:16:38,806
after they had it?

531
00:16:38,873 --> 00:16:40,416
To shake something loose,

532
00:16:40,483 --> 00:16:42,890
investigators went public in a way they

533
00:16:42,957 --> 00:16:43,957
rarely do.

534
00:16:44,024 --> 00:16:46,246
They launched an appeal to the whole

535
00:16:46,313 --> 00:16:47,313
country —

536
00:16:47,380 --> 00:16:49,602
a dedicated website, images of every

537
00:16:49,669 --> 00:16:51,891
missing work, even billboards in the

538
00:16:51,958 --> 00:16:54,180
region where the trail had last been

539
00:16:54,247 --> 00:16:55,247
warm.

540
00:16:55,314 --> 00:16:56,733
The message was simple,

541
00:16:56,800 --> 00:16:59,331
and a little desperate: someone out there

542
00:16:59,398 --> 00:17:00,509
has seen this art.

543
00:17:00,576 --> 00:17:01,576
On a wall.

544
00:17:01,643 --> 00:17:02,643
In an attic.

545
00:17:02,710 --> 00:17:03,710
In a back room.

546
00:17:03,777 --> 00:17:05,629
We need that person to pick up

547
00:17:05,696 --> 00:17:06,696
the phone.

548
00:17:06,763 --> 00:17:08,800
On that, the FBI offered its best

549
00:17:08,867 --> 00:17:09,867
answer.

550
00:17:09,934 --> 00:17:12,156
It said the investigation traced the

551
00:17:12,223 --> 00:17:13,951
stolen works out of Boston —

552
00:17:14,018 --> 00:17:15,931
to Connecticut, and then to the

553
00:17:15,998 --> 00:17:17,109
Philadelphia area.

554
00:17:17,176 --> 00:17:18,225
And it said that,

555
00:17:18,292 --> 00:17:20,267
roughly a decade before the 2013

556
00:17:20,334 --> 00:17:22,679
announcement, some of the art had been

557
00:17:22,746 --> 00:17:24,783
offered for sale in Philadelphia.

558
00:17:24,850 --> 00:17:26,825
After that, the trail goes cold.

559
00:17:26,892 --> 00:17:27,941
The FBI has said,

560
00:17:28,008 --> 00:17:30,168
in effect: we followed it this far,

561
00:17:30,235 --> 00:17:31,469
and then we lost it.

562
00:17:31,536 --> 00:17:33,141
We do not know where it is

563
00:17:33,208 --> 00:17:34,208
now.

564
00:17:34,275 --> 00:17:36,312
Think about how a trail like that

565
00:17:36,379 --> 00:17:37,379
goes cold.

566
00:17:37,446 --> 00:17:39,730
Stolen art that cannot be sold openly

567
00:17:39,797 --> 00:17:42,081
tends to drift through a hidden world

568
00:17:42,148 --> 00:17:43,148
—

569
00:17:43,215 --> 00:17:45,128
used as collateral, as a favor,

570
00:17:45,195 --> 00:17:46,985
as a chip in some other deal,

571
00:17:47,052 --> 00:17:49,150
passed from hand to hand by people

572
00:17:49,217 --> 00:17:51,439
who have every reason never to talk.

573
00:17:51,506 --> 00:17:53,172
Each time it changes hands,

574
00:17:53,239 --> 00:17:55,399
the knowledge of where it sits gets

575
00:17:55,466 --> 00:17:57,688
thinner, and the people who hold the

576
00:17:57,755 --> 00:17:58,804
secret get fewer.

577
00:17:58,871 --> 00:18:00,661
By the time the FBI traced it

578
00:18:00,728 --> 00:18:03,320
to Philadelphia, it may already have moved

579
00:18:03,387 --> 00:18:04,387
again.

580
00:18:04,454 --> 00:18:06,244
A painting can be hidden in a

581
00:18:06,311 --> 00:18:07,311
single room.

582
00:18:07,378 --> 00:18:09,415
The truth about where it went can

583
00:18:09,482 --> 00:18:11,580
be hidden inside a single person —

584
00:18:11,647 --> 00:18:13,560
and people do not last forever.

585
00:18:13,627 --> 00:18:15,602
And there is one more twist that

586
00:18:15,669 --> 00:18:17,891
changes the whole shape of the hunt.

587
00:18:17,958 --> 00:18:20,365
The statute of limitations on the theft

588
00:18:20,432 --> 00:18:21,605
itself has expired.

589
00:18:21,672 --> 00:18:23,770
In plain terms: even if you walked

590
00:18:23,837 --> 00:18:26,182
into an FBI office today and confessed

591
00:18:26,249 --> 00:18:28,594
to robbing the Gardner Museum in 1990,

592
00:18:28,661 --> 00:18:30,821
you could not be prosecuted for the

593
00:18:30,888 --> 00:18:31,888
theft.

594
00:18:31,955 --> 00:18:33,621
The clock ran out long ago.

595
00:18:33,688 --> 00:18:35,910
At first that sounds like a failure.

596
00:18:35,977 --> 00:18:37,582
But it is actually a tool.

597
00:18:37,649 --> 00:18:39,994
Because it means the people who matter

598
00:18:40,061 --> 00:18:41,913
most now are not the thieves —

599
00:18:41,980 --> 00:18:44,387
they are whoever is quietly holding the

600
00:18:44,454 --> 00:18:45,454
art.

601
00:18:45,521 --> 00:18:46,755
And to those people,

602
00:18:46,822 --> 00:18:49,106
the message from prosecutors has been

603
00:18:49,173 --> 00:18:51,148
remarkably open: we are far more

604
00:18:51,215 --> 00:18:53,560
interested in getting these works back

605
00:18:53,627 --> 00:18:55,479
than in putting you in a cell.

606
00:18:55,546 --> 00:18:57,706
They have signaled a willingness to

607
00:18:57,773 --> 00:18:58,884
consider immunity.

608
00:18:58,951 --> 00:19:01,235
There is a ten-million-dollar reward.

609
00:19:01,302 --> 00:19:03,215
You would not even have to hand

610
00:19:03,282 --> 00:19:05,072
the paintings over in person.

611
00:19:05,139 --> 00:19:07,114
And the museum has tried to make

612
00:19:07,181 --> 00:19:09,403
saying something as easy and as safe

613
00:19:09,470 --> 00:19:10,643
as it possibly can.

614
00:19:10,710 --> 00:19:12,932
The ten-million-dollar reward is for

615
00:19:12,999 --> 00:19:15,530
information that leads to the recovery of

616
00:19:15,597 --> 00:19:17,881
all thirteen works in good condition.

617
00:19:17,948 --> 00:19:19,923
You would not have to march into

618
00:19:19,990 --> 00:19:21,039
a police station.

619
00:19:21,106 --> 00:19:23,081
You could work through a lawyer,

620
00:19:23,148 --> 00:19:25,740
protect your identity, keep your distance.

621
00:19:25,807 --> 00:19:27,967
The whole offer is built around one

622
00:19:28,034 --> 00:19:30,379
almost gentle idea: we are not hunting

623
00:19:30,446 --> 00:19:31,446
you —

624
00:19:31,513 --> 00:19:32,932
we just want them back.

625
00:19:32,999 --> 00:19:34,172
Bring the art home,

626
00:19:34,239 --> 00:19:35,658
and there is a fortune,

627
00:19:35,725 --> 00:19:37,206
and a measure of safety,

628
00:19:37,273 --> 00:19:38,273
waiting.

629
00:19:38,340 --> 00:19:40,253
The whole machinery of the law,

630
00:19:40,320 --> 00:19:42,789
in other words, has been quietly rebuilt

631
00:19:42,856 --> 00:19:44,214
around a single goal —

632
00:19:44,281 --> 00:19:45,886
not justice for the theft,

633
00:19:45,953 --> 00:19:47,434
which is now impossible,

634
00:19:47,501 --> 00:19:49,908
but the return of thirteen objects that

635
00:19:49,975 --> 00:19:51,148
cannot be replaced.

636
00:19:51,215 --> 00:19:53,128
So if the FBI believes it knows

637
00:19:53,195 --> 00:19:54,800
who did it, and there is a

638
00:19:54,867 --> 00:19:57,274
fortune waiting for whoever returns the

639
00:19:57,341 --> 00:19:59,007
art, and no one even has to

640
00:19:59,074 --> 00:20:00,740
fear prison for the theft —

641
00:20:00,807 --> 00:20:02,720
why are the frames still empty?

642
00:20:02,787 --> 00:20:04,700
That is the real mystery of the

643
00:20:04,767 --> 00:20:05,767
Gardner case.

644
00:20:05,834 --> 00:20:07,192
Not so much whodunit —

645
00:20:07,259 --> 00:20:08,740
but why, after all this,

646
00:20:08,807 --> 00:20:09,980
nothing comes back.

647
00:20:10,489 --> 00:20:13,082
There are really only a few possibilities,

648
00:20:13,149 --> 00:20:15,124
and none of them is comfortable.

649
00:20:15,707 --> 00:20:17,312
The first is the simplest,

650
00:20:17,379 --> 00:20:18,379
and the worst.

651
00:20:18,560 --> 00:20:20,510
The art may be gone —

652
00:20:20,577 --> 00:20:21,577
destroyed.

653
00:20:22,100 --> 00:20:24,199
Stolen goods this hot are a danger

654
00:20:24,266 --> 00:20:26,056
to everyone who touches them.

655
00:20:26,220 --> 00:20:28,689
Someone, at some point in three decades,

656
00:20:28,756 --> 00:20:31,101
may have decided that the safest thing

657
00:20:31,168 --> 00:20:32,896
to do with a painting no one

658
00:20:32,963 --> 00:20:34,938
can sell is to make it disappear

659
00:20:35,005 --> 00:20:36,005
for good.

660
00:20:36,072 --> 00:20:37,072
If that is true,

661
00:20:37,139 --> 00:20:39,361
the empty frames are not waiting for

662
00:20:39,428 --> 00:20:40,428
anything.

663
00:20:40,495 --> 00:20:41,791
They are gravestones.

664
00:20:41,858 --> 00:20:43,648
The second is that the art is

665
00:20:43,715 --> 00:20:45,578
still out there —

666
00:20:45,645 --> 00:20:46,879
sitting in an attic,

667
00:20:46,946 --> 00:20:49,146
a storage unit, a basement —

668
00:20:49,213 --> 00:20:51,250
held by someone who inherited it,

669
00:20:51,317 --> 00:20:52,490
or is afraid of it,

670
00:20:52,557 --> 00:20:54,594
or simply does not know what they

671
00:20:54,661 --> 00:20:55,661
have.

672
00:20:55,728 --> 00:20:57,950
Masterpieces have resurfaced before,

673
00:20:58,017 --> 00:21:00,115
decades later, in stranger places.

674
00:21:00,182 --> 00:21:02,589
The reward exists precisely because the

675
00:21:02,656 --> 00:21:04,754
FBI and the museum believe this is

676
00:21:04,821 --> 00:21:05,821
possible.

677
00:21:05,888 --> 00:21:07,801
And the third is the quiet ache

678
00:21:07,868 --> 00:21:09,534
underneath the whole case —

679
00:21:09,601 --> 00:21:11,699
that the few people who truly knew

680
00:21:11,766 --> 00:21:13,926
where it went have taken the answer

681
00:21:13,993 --> 00:21:14,993
to their graves.

682
00:21:15,060 --> 00:21:16,541
If the thieves are dead,

683
00:21:16,608 --> 00:21:18,274
and the middlemen are dead,

684
00:21:18,341 --> 00:21:20,501
then the location of half a billion

685
00:21:20,568 --> 00:21:22,481
dollars in art may now exist in

686
00:21:22,548 --> 00:21:23,906
no living mind at all.

687
00:21:24,352 --> 00:21:26,266
The leading theory, the one law

688
00:21:26,333 --> 00:21:28,925
enforcement's own statements point toward,

689
00:21:28,992 --> 00:21:30,720
is that this was the work of

690
00:21:30,787 --> 00:21:31,836
organized crime —

691
00:21:31,903 --> 00:21:34,248
local criminals who saw an easy target

692
00:21:34,315 --> 00:21:35,540
and a famous prize,

693
00:21:36,940 --> 00:21:38,915
and who may have grabbed the art

694
00:21:38,982 --> 00:21:44,140
with only a vague idea of how

695
00:21:44,207 --> 00:21:49,420
to ever turn it into money.

696
00:21:49,487 --> 00:21:52,920
That would explain the strange,

697
00:21:52,987 --> 00:21:53,987
amateurish haul.

698
00:21:54,054 --> 00:21:57,400
It would explain why nothing was ever

699
00:21:57,467 --> 00:21:58,467
quietly sold.

700
00:21:58,534 --> 00:22:00,756
And it would explain the silence: in

701
00:22:00,823 --> 00:22:03,260
that world, the people who know things

702
00:22:03,327 --> 00:22:05,364
are exactly the people who never,

703
00:22:05,431 --> 00:22:06,431
ever say them.

704
00:22:06,498 --> 00:22:08,041
If that is what happened,

705
00:22:08,108 --> 00:22:10,083
then the art was less a treasure

706
00:22:10,150 --> 00:22:11,150
than a curse —

707
00:22:11,217 --> 00:22:12,217
too hot to sell,

708
00:22:12,284 --> 00:22:13,457
too famous to show,

709
00:22:13,524 --> 00:22:15,190
too valuable to throw away.

710
00:22:15,257 --> 00:22:17,170
And woven through all of it are

711
00:22:17,237 --> 00:22:19,829
the smaller mysteries that never resolved.

712
00:22:19,896 --> 00:22:22,303
Like the strange detail from inside the

713
00:22:22,370 --> 00:22:24,530
museum that night: according to the

714
00:22:24,597 --> 00:22:26,325
museum's own security chief,

715
00:22:26,392 --> 00:22:28,737
the motion sensors recorded no one but

716
00:22:28,804 --> 00:22:30,779
a guard ever entering one of the

717
00:22:30,846 --> 00:22:32,821
rooms a painting was taken from.

718
00:22:32,888 --> 00:22:34,863
A work vanished from a space the

719
00:22:34,930 --> 00:22:37,522
system says the thieves never walked into.

720
00:22:37,589 --> 00:22:39,194
A small, maddening puzzle,

721
00:22:39,261 --> 00:22:41,359
decades old, with no clean answer.

722
00:22:41,426 --> 00:22:43,154
And there is a human cost to

723
00:22:43,221 --> 00:22:45,134
an open wound like this that is

724
00:22:45,201 --> 00:22:46,744
easy to forget behind the

725
00:22:46,811 --> 00:22:48,601
half-billion-dollar headline.

726
00:22:48,668 --> 00:22:50,705
A museum that has spent more than

727
00:22:50,772 --> 00:22:52,624
three decades as the site of a

728
00:22:52,691 --> 00:22:53,691
famous loss.

729
00:22:53,758 --> 00:22:56,165
A city that quietly adopted the mystery

730
00:22:56,232 --> 00:22:57,232
as its own.

731
00:22:57,299 --> 00:22:59,583
Investigators who gave years of their

732
00:22:59,650 --> 00:23:01,625
careers to a case that never let

733
00:23:01,692 --> 00:23:02,865
them reach the end.

734
00:23:02,932 --> 00:23:05,277
And, somewhere, two men who were young

735
00:23:05,344 --> 00:23:07,566
guards on an ordinary shift and have

736
00:23:07,633 --> 00:23:10,102
carried that night with them ever since.

737
00:23:10,169 --> 00:23:12,082
The empty frames are a loss for

738
00:23:12,149 --> 00:23:13,322
the history of art.

739
00:23:13,389 --> 00:23:15,364
They are also a loss measured in

740
00:23:15,431 --> 00:23:16,431
ordinary lives.

741
00:23:16,498 --> 00:23:18,720
This is what makes the Gardner heist

742
00:23:18,787 --> 00:23:21,194
different from the crimes that get tidy

743
00:23:21,261 --> 00:23:22,261
endings.

744
00:23:22,328 --> 00:23:23,994
There is no trial to watch.

745
00:23:24,061 --> 00:23:25,666
No verdict to argue about.

746
00:23:25,733 --> 00:23:27,893
No moment where a detective lays it

747
00:23:27,960 --> 00:23:29,750
all out and the pieces click.

748
00:23:29,817 --> 00:23:32,101
There is only a slowly cooling trail,

749
00:23:32,168 --> 00:23:34,205
a list of names that never became

750
00:23:34,272 --> 00:23:36,679
charges, and a building that decided to

751
00:23:36,746 --> 00:23:38,042
leave the wound open.

752
00:23:38,109 --> 00:23:40,331
You would think a ten-million-dollar

753
00:23:40,398 --> 00:23:42,743
reward would be enough to break almost

754
00:23:42,810 --> 00:23:43,810
any silence.

755
00:23:43,877 --> 00:23:45,914
The fact that it hasn't tells you

756
00:23:45,981 --> 00:23:48,326
something cold about where the art may

757
00:23:48,393 --> 00:23:49,393
have gone.

758
00:23:49,460 --> 00:23:51,682
Either the people who could claim it

759
00:23:51,749 --> 00:23:54,033
are dead, or they are more frightened

760
00:23:54,100 --> 00:23:56,384
of something than they are tempted by

761
00:23:56,451 --> 00:23:58,858
ten million dollars, or there is simply

762
00:23:58,925 --> 00:24:00,591
nothing left to bring back.

763
00:24:00,658 --> 00:24:01,892
A reward that large,

764
00:24:01,959 --> 00:24:03,440
unclaimed for this long,

765
00:24:03,507 --> 00:24:05,112
stops being just an offer.

766
00:24:05,179 --> 00:24:06,475
It becomes evidence —

767
00:24:06,542 --> 00:24:09,134
that whatever happened to the Gardner art,

768
00:24:09,201 --> 00:24:11,299
it is buried deeper than money can

769
00:24:11,366 --> 00:24:12,366
reach.

770
00:24:12,433 --> 00:24:14,038
Because that was a choice.

771
00:24:14,105 --> 00:24:16,697
The museum could have quietly filled those

772
00:24:16,764 --> 00:24:17,764
spaces —

773
00:24:17,831 --> 00:24:19,189
moved a painting over,

774
00:24:19,256 --> 00:24:21,663
hung something new, let the walls heal.

775
00:24:21,730 --> 00:24:24,075
Instead, the empty frames stay exactly

776
00:24:24,142 --> 00:24:25,870
where the stolen works hung.

777
00:24:25,937 --> 00:24:28,529
In part because Isabella Stewart Gardner's

778
00:24:28,596 --> 00:24:31,003
own wishes asked that her collection be

779
00:24:31,070 --> 00:24:32,551
kept as she arranged it.

780
00:24:32,618 --> 00:24:35,149
And in part as something more deliberate:

781
00:24:35,216 --> 00:24:37,561
a refusal to pretend it didn't happen,

782
00:24:37,628 --> 00:24:39,850
and a standing, public hope that one

783
00:24:39,917 --> 00:24:42,139
day the frames will be filled again.

784
00:24:42,206 --> 00:24:44,428
Every visitor who stands in front of

785
00:24:44,495 --> 00:24:46,532
one of those frames is looking at

786
00:24:46,599 --> 00:24:49,006
the same thing the thieves left behind.

787
00:24:49,073 --> 00:24:50,073
Not a painting.

788
00:24:50,140 --> 00:24:51,140
A question.

789
00:24:51,207 --> 00:24:52,812
More than thirty years on,

790
00:24:52,879 --> 00:24:55,163
the Gardner heist has outlived almost

791
00:24:55,230 --> 00:24:56,773
everyone connected to it.

792
00:24:56,840 --> 00:24:58,013
The guards grew up.

793
00:24:58,080 --> 00:24:59,993
The lead investigators retired.

794
00:25:00,060 --> 00:25:01,973
The men the FBI believes did it

795
00:25:02,040 --> 00:25:03,521
are, by its own account,

796
00:25:03,588 --> 00:25:04,588
gone.

797
00:25:04,655 --> 00:25:07,062
And still, the most valuable stolen art

798
00:25:07,129 --> 00:25:09,166
on earth is out there somewhere —

799
00:25:09,233 --> 00:25:10,233
or it isn't —

800
00:25:10,300 --> 00:25:12,028
and the frames keep waiting.

801
00:25:12,095 --> 00:25:14,132
It is tempting to want a villain,

802
00:25:14,199 --> 00:25:15,680
a name, a face to blame.

803
00:25:15,747 --> 00:25:17,969
But the honest version of this story

804
00:25:18,036 --> 00:25:19,517
is harder, and stranger.

805
00:25:19,584 --> 00:25:21,436
It is a crime that has slipped

806
00:25:21,503 --> 00:25:23,108
past the reach of the law,

807
00:25:23,175 --> 00:25:25,150
past the lives of the people who

808
00:25:25,217 --> 00:25:27,809
committed it, and into something closer to

809
00:25:27,876 --> 00:25:28,876
a legend —

810
00:25:28,943 --> 00:25:31,412
except that the loss is completely real,

811
00:25:31,479 --> 00:25:33,145
and it is hanging on a wall

812
00:25:33,212 --> 00:25:34,446
in Boston right now.

813
00:25:34,513 --> 00:25:36,365
And maybe that is why it holds

814
00:25:36,432 --> 00:25:37,432
us.

815
00:25:37,499 --> 00:25:39,597
We are used to stories that close.

816
00:25:39,664 --> 00:25:41,145
This one simply refuses.

817
00:25:41,212 --> 00:25:43,804
Somewhere, perhaps, a Vermeer is rolled in

818
00:25:43,871 --> 00:25:45,044
a tube in the dark.

819
00:25:45,111 --> 00:25:46,407
Or perhaps it is ash.

820
00:25:46,474 --> 00:25:47,474
We do not know.

821
00:25:47,541 --> 00:25:49,886
And the not-knowing is the whole point

822
00:25:49,953 --> 00:25:50,953
—

823
00:25:51,020 --> 00:25:53,612
a half-billion-dollar question, with empty

824
00:25:53,679 --> 00:25:56,086
gold frames where the answer should be.

825
00:25:56,153 --> 00:25:58,745
There is something almost unbearable about

826
00:25:58,812 --> 00:26:00,540
a loss that just stays open.

827
00:26:00,607 --> 00:26:01,965
A murder gets a trial.

828
00:26:02,032 --> 00:26:03,266
A war gets a treaty.

829
00:26:03,333 --> 00:26:05,555
Even most thefts end with a recovery

830
00:26:05,622 --> 00:26:06,622
or an arrest or,

831
00:26:06,689 --> 00:26:08,170
at least, a closed file.

832
00:26:08,237 --> 00:26:10,397
The Gardner heist gives you none of

833
00:26:10,464 --> 00:26:11,464
that.

834
00:26:11,531 --> 00:26:13,259
It asks you to live with not

835
00:26:13,326 --> 00:26:14,326
knowing —

836
00:26:14,393 --> 00:26:16,862
to accept that one ordinary March night,

837
00:26:16,929 --> 00:26:19,213
thirteen pieces of the world's memory

838
00:26:19,280 --> 00:26:20,391
walked out a door,

839
00:26:20,458 --> 00:26:22,371
and that they may be sitting in

840
00:26:22,438 --> 00:26:24,228
the dark somewhere right now,

841
00:26:24,295 --> 00:26:25,714
or may be gone forever,

842
00:26:25,781 --> 00:26:27,879
and that both of those things feel

843
00:26:27,946 --> 00:26:30,106
equally possible and equally wrong.

844
00:26:30,173 --> 00:26:32,148
If those frames ever fill again,

845
00:26:32,215 --> 00:26:34,560
it will likely be because one ordinary

846
00:26:34,627 --> 00:26:35,627
person —

847
00:26:35,694 --> 00:26:37,299
someone who saw something,

848
00:26:37,366 --> 00:26:39,094
in an attic, a storage unit,

849
00:26:39,161 --> 00:26:40,334
a quiet back room —

850
00:26:40,401 --> 00:26:42,314
finally decided to make a call.

851
00:26:42,381 --> 00:26:43,615
After all this time,

852
00:26:43,682 --> 00:26:45,287
that is still how it ends.

853
00:26:45,354 --> 00:26:46,650
Not with a detective.

854
00:26:46,717 --> 00:26:47,717
With a witness.

855
00:26:48,944 --> 00:26:51,039
So while those frames wait —

856
00:26:51,106 --> 00:26:53,513
do one small thing that actually helps.

